Hepatitis A Southeast Michigan Outbreak
---------------------------------------
Since the beginning of the outbreak in August 2016, public health response has included increased healthcare awareness efforts, public notification and education, and outreach with vaccination clinics for high-risk populations. No common sources of food, beverages, or drugs have been identified as a potential source of infection. Transmission appears to be through direct person-to-person spread and illicit drug use. Those with history of injection and non-injection drug use, homelessness or transient housing, and incarceration are thought to be at greater risk in this outbreak setting. Notably, this outbreak has had a high hospitalization rate.

Southeast Michigan Hepatitis A Outbreak Cases and Deaths as of 3 Nov 2017
Cases / Hospitalizations / Deaths
486 / 409 (84.2 percent) / 19 (3.9 percent)

Please note: Affected jurisdictions include City of Detroit, and Huron, Lapeer, Livingston, Macomb, Monroe, Oakland, St. Clair, Sanilac, Washtenaw & Wayne Counties. [Data above] does not include all reported hepatitis A cases in the region; only those that are identified as outbreak-related. More descriptive data on the current outbreak can be found within the Comprehensive Summary [see below]. Data are provisional and subject to change.

Detailed breakdown of the total includes (but excludes secondary cases)
Female, n (percent): 179 (36.8)
Hospitalized, n (percent): 409 (84.2)
No substance abuse plus no homeless/transient living, n (percent): 158 (35.3)
Documented substance abuse, n (percent): 222 (49.7)
Homeless/transient living, n (percent): 50 (11.2)
History of hepatitis B, n (percent): 14 (3.1)
History of hepatitis C, n (percent): 131 (29.3)
MSM, n (percent) *Data include only male cases: 25 (8.6)
Correctional facility inmates, n (percent): 30 (6.7)
Healthcare worker, n (percent): 10 (2.2)
Food worker, n (percent): 18 (4.0)
Deaths, n (percent): 19 (4.2)

